Let S be a <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_14" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=388" >semigroup</a>. An <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_13" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=2604" >idempotent</a> eS is <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_12" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=6153" >primitive</a> if for every other idempotent <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_11" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=3264" >fS</a> , ef=fe=f=0e=f

A semigroup S (without <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_10" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=10602" >zero</a>) is <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_9" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=6153" >completely simple</a> if it is <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_8" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=5905" >simple</a> and <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_7" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=1635" >contains</a> a primitive idempotent.

A semigroup S is completely 0 -simple if it is 0 -simple and contains a primitive idempotent.

Completely simple and completely 0 -<a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_6" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=3521" >simple semigroups</a> maybe characterised by the Rees <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_5" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=4492" >Theorem</a> ([Ho95], Theorem 3.2.3).

Note:

A semigroup (without zero) is completely simple if and only if it is <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_4" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=2256" >regular</a> and <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_3" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=5926" >weakly cancellative</a>.

A simple semigroup (without zero) is completely simple if and only if it is <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_2" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=1534" >completely regular</a>.

A 0 -simple semigroup is completely 0 -simple if and only if it is <a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_1" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=78" >group</a>-<a class="PlanetMath_autolink" id="autolink_0" href="http://planetmath.org/?op=getobj;from=objects;id=450" >bound</a>.
</body></html>